apkenv — Android NDK game host for webOS (HP TouchPad)
======================================================

This webOS PDK app runs an Android NDK game *natively* on webOS, with NO ACL
(OpenMobile's full Android runtime) and NO Dalvik. It is a slim apkenv-based
shim: a gingerbread bionic linker loaded as a library + a fake-JNI layer + a
webOS SDL/PDL backend + a per-game module. The Android game's own native .so
(its engine) is loaded and driven directly through its JNI entry points.

LAYOUT OF THIS APP DIRECTORY
----------------------------
  apkenv            The host binary (native ARM ELF). This is the apkenv runtime
                    compiled for webOS. On launch it self-locates (/proc/self/exe),
                    cd's here, picks the game under android/, and runs it.
  appinfo.json      webOS app manifest (type:pdk, main:apkenv).
  icon.png          Launcher icon.
  README            This file.

  libs/             webOS-SIDE host libraries (the "left half" of the shim).
    webos/          apkenv loads these with its OWN userspace linker:
      libc.so         } harvested Android 2.3 (gingerbread) bionic libraries —
      libm.so         } the runtime the game's native code was built against.
      libstdc++.so    }
      liblog.so       }
      libz.so         }
      libdvm_compat.so  (unused unless Dalvik mode is on)
      libEGL.so       webOS device EGL (pulled from the TouchPad).

  android/          THE ANDROID BITS (the "right half" — the game itself).
    *.apk           The Android NDK game, shipped whole. apkenv reads the
                    engine's native libs (lib/armeabi-v7a/*.so) and all assets
                    straight out of this .apk at runtime. For "Where's My Water?"
                    this is wheresmywater.apk, with a 1-instruction libwmw patch
                    baked in (std::string(NULL) -> "" instead of throwing).

RUNTIME-WRITABLE DATA (not in this dir — the app dir is read-only at runtime)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  /media/internal/.apkenv/<apk-basename>/   savegames + the apk's extracted
                                            native libs (apkenv writes here).
  /media/internal/apkenv-wmw.log            this app's stdout/stderr (a jailed
                                            PDK app's stdio goes nowhere else).

RE-PACKING A DIFFERENT GAME
---------------------------
1. Drop the new game's .apk into android/ (remove the old one). apkenv launches
   the first *.apk it finds there.
2. Most games need a per-game MODULE (the apkenv source tree, modules/<game>.c):
   it calls the game's real JNI entry points (rendererInit / drawFrame / touch /
   lifecycle) with faked args, since there is no Java Activity. "Where's My
   Water?" uses the built-in `wheresmywater` module. A new engine = a new module
   (find its entry points with `baksmali` on classes.dex + readelf on the .so).
3. Rebuild apkenv (build-webos.sh) and re-run packaging/build-ipk.sh.

See the project tree (apkenv/) for the full source, build recipe, and the
reverse-engineering notes (BUILD-STATE.md, ../plan/, android-port-shim.md).
